'''1ES 1101-232''' is an active galactic nucleus of a distant galaxy known as a [[blazar]].

An X-ray source (catalogued as A 1059-22) was first recorded by Maccagni and colleagues in a 1978 paper; they thought the source arose from a galaxy in the [[Abell 1146]] galaxy cluster, which contained many giant elliptical galaxies.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Maccagni |first1=D.|last2= Tarenghi | first2= M.|last3=Cooke| first3= B. A.|last4= Maccacaro| first4= T.|last5=Pye| first5= J. P.|last6= Ricketts| first6= M. J. |title=An X-ray and optical study of seven clusters of galaxies |journal=Astronomy and Astrophysics |date=1978 |volume=62 |issue=1-2 |pages=127–33 | bibcode=1978A&A....62..127M}}</ref> In 1989, Remillard and colleagues linked the X-ray source with a visual object and established that the object was surrounded by a large elliptical galaxy. They also discovered that the object (and galaxy) were more distant, with a redshift of 0.186.<ref>{{cite journal | title=Two X-ray-selected BL Lacertae objects observed with the HEAO 1 scanning modulation collimator |last1=Remillard| first1= R. A.|last2=Tuohy| first2= I. R.|last3=Brissenden| first3= R. J. V.|last4=Buckley| first4= D. A. H.|last5=Schwartz| first5=D. A.|last6=Feigelson| first6= E. D.|last7=Tapia| first7= S. | journal= Astrophysical Journal, Part 1 | issn= 0004-637X| volume= 345|year= 1989| pages= 140–47 | doi= 10.1086/167888 |bibcode=1989ApJ...345..140R}}</ref> The host galaxy appears to be part of a distant galaxy cluster.<ref>{{cite journal | title=Imaging and spectroscopy of galaxies in the fields of five BL Lacertae objects |last1= Pesce | first1= Joseph E.| last2= Falomo| first2= Renato. | last3=Treves| first3= Aldo | journal= Astronomical Journal | issn= 0004-6256| volume= 107| issue= 2| pages= 494–502 | year=1994 | doi= 10.1086/116871 |bibcode=1994AJ....107..494P}}</ref>

