[[File:A591 road, Lake District - June 2009 Edit 1.jpg|thumb|right|400px|The A591 as it passes between Ambleside and Grasmere]]
The '''A591''' is a major road in [[Cumbria]], in the north-west of [[England]], which lies almost entirely within the [[Lake District]] national park.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.co.uk/maps/dir/54.2762057,-2.7628439/54.7355768,-3.2735792/@54.5251929,-3.2201612,10z/data=!3m1!4b1!4m2!4m1!3e0 |work=[[Google Maps]] |accessdate=19 October 2018}}</ref> A 2009 poll by satellite navigation firm [[Garmin]] named the stretch of the road between [[Windermere, Cumbria (town)|Windermere]] and [[Keswick, Cumbria|Keswick]] as the most popular road in Britain.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.garmin.com/en-GB/blog/end-of-the-road-for-the-great-british-drive/ |work=Garmin |title=End of the Road for the Great British Drive – UK roads drive motorists to despair |date=2 March 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Britain's Favourite Road|url=http://www.britainsfavouriteview.co.uk/Road.asp |accessdate=22 December 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090619074030/http://www.britainsfavouriteview.co.uk/Road.asp |archivedate=19 June 2009 }}</ref> The 29.8 mile stretch between Kendal and Keswick was also named the UK's best driving road, according to a specially devised driving ratio formulated by car rental firm [[Avis Europe|Avis]].<ref>https://leasing.com/car-leasing-news/uks-best-driving-roads-revealed/</ref>

==Route==
The road begins (at its southern end) {{convert|3.5|mi}} north-west of junction 36 of the [[M6 motorway]] at [[Brettargh Holt]] [[roundabout]] with the [[A590 road]] {{nowrap|({{coord|54.2746|-2.7605|type:landmark_region:GB|display=inline|name=A591 road (southern end)}}),}} close to [[Sizergh Castle]].<ref>{{cite book |isbn=9780319263334 |title=Map of The Lake District: South-eastern area (Sheet OL7) |publisher=[[Ordnance Survey]] |year=2017 |url=https://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/shop/explorer-map-the-lake-district-south-eastern-area.html}}</ref> It bypasses the town of [[Kendal]] as a [[dual carriageway]], this £1.9m {{convert|3|mi|adj=on}} section opened on 29 August 1971. It becomes a busy [[single carriageway]] road as it enters the [[Lake District]]. It bypasses the town of [[Windermere, Cumbria (town)|Windermere]],  closely following the north-eastern bank of [[Windermere|Lake Windermere]]. It then travels through the centre of [[Ambleside]], follows the northern side of [[Rydal Water]], passes White Moss Common, follows the eastern edge of [[Grasmere (lake)|Grasmere]] and passes the [[Grasmere (village)|village of Grasmere]]. The road continues over [[Dunmail Raise]] and along the eastern edge of [[Thirlmere]]. Shortly afterwards it reaches the town of [[Keswick, Cumbria|Keswick]]. It meets the [[A66 road]] at a grade-separated junction. Traffic then bypasses Keswick by following the A66 west for 2.2&nbsp;km to a roundabout where the A591 resumes, continuing in a roughly north-westerly direction, with fine views over [[Bassenthwaite Lake]]. The road terminates at the village of [[Bothel, Cumbria|Bothel]], on the [[A595 road]] {{nowrap|({{coord|54.7357|-3.2733|type:landmark_region:GB|display=inline|name=A591 road (northern end)}}).}}<ref>{{cite book |isbn=9780319242438 |title=Map of The Lake District: North-western area (Sheet OL4) |publisher=[[Ordnance Survey]] |year=2017 |url=https://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/shop/explorer-map-the-lake-district-south-eastern-area.html}}</ref> The Bothel-to-Keswick section has many acute bends and is particularly narrow in places, leading to many accidents{{citation needed|date=December 2015}}. 

===Storm damage and closure===
The road was badly damaged during [[Storm Desmond]] on 5 December 2015 including a part washed away at Dunmail Raise and landslip adjacent to Thirlmere.  The closed section of road between Grasmere and [[Legburthwaite]] reopened on 11 May 2016.<ref>{{cite new |title=Storm Desmond: A591 reopens ahead of schedule |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-cumbria-36262619/ |work=BBC News |date=11 May 2016 |accessdate= 18 May 2016}}</ref> While the road was closed a new trail for walkers, cyclists, and horseriders was built to the west of the road at Dunmail Raise.<ref>{{cite news |title=New trail to link flood-hit lakeland at Dunmail Rise |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-cumbria-36151496 |author=BBC News |date=28 April 2016}}</ref>

