{{Infobox scientist | name = Peter Ascanius | image = Ascanius portrett.JPG | birth_date = {{Birth date|1723|05|24|df=yes}} | birth_place = [[Aure, Norway|Aure]], Møre og Romsdal, Norway. | death_date = {{Death date and age|1803|06|04|1723|05|24|df=yes}} | death_place = [[Copenhagen, Denmark]] | resting_place = | other_names = | citizenship = [[Norway|Norwegian]] | nationality = | fields = [[Biologist]] | academic_advisors = [[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]] | known_for = | awards = | spouse = | children = }}
'''Peter Ascanius''' (24 May 1723 – 4 June 1803) was a [[Norway|Norwegian]] [[biologist]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.nhm.uio.no/forskning/aktuelt/arrangementer/konferanser-seminarer/2011/bergseminaret-berg-o.pdf|title= Peder Ascanius (1723-1803) |publisher = Naturhistorisk Museum, UiO |author= |accessdate= January 1, 2017 }}</ref>
He was born at [[Aure, Norway|Aure]] in Møre og Romsdal, Norway. He was a student of [[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]]. He taught [[zoology]] and [[mineralogy]] in [[Copenhagen]] from 1759 to 1771, and later worked as a supervisor at the mines in [[Kongsberg]] and elsewhere in Norway. Among his published works was the five-volume illustrated ''Icones rerum naturalium''. He was a [[Royal Society|Fellow of the Royal Society]], elected in 1755 as a Foreign Member.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://royalsociety.org/DServe/dserve.exe?dsqIni=Dserve.ini&dsqApp=Archive&dsqCmd=Show.tcl&dsqDb=Persons&dsqPos=0&dsqSearch=%28%28text%29%3D%27NA7938%27%29|title=Fellow details|accessdate=14 October 2012|publisher=royalsociety.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://snl.no/Peter_Ascanius|title= Peder Ascanius |publisher = Store norske leksikon |author= Rune S. Selbekk|accessdate= January 1, 2017 }}</ref>
Ascanius first described the [[giant oarfish]] in 1772.<ref>{{cite news |title= Legendary Giant Oarfish that grows up to 50ft long and lives nearly a MILE undersea recorded in its natural environment for first time |author= |url= http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2338200/VIDEO-Scientist-believe-captured-mysterious-Giant-Oarfish-camera-time.html |newspaper= Mail Online ([[Daily Mail]]) |location= United Kingdom |date= June 8, 2013 |accessdate= June 22, 2013 |archiveurl= https://www.webcitation.org/6HZgRWH1C?url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2338200/VIDEO-Scientist-believe-captured-mysterious-Giant-Oarfish-camera-time.html |archivedate= June 22, 2013 |deadurl= no |df= }}</ref>
