{{distinguish|sponge reef}}
'''Sponge grounds''', also known as '''sponge aggregations''', are [[Intertidal zone|intertidal]] to [[Deep sea|deep-sea]] habitats formed by large accumulations of [[sponge]]s ([[Hexactinellid|glass sponges]] and/or [[demosponge]]s), often dominated by a few massive species. Sponge grounds were already reported more than 150 years ago,<ref name=UNEP2010>{{cite journal| authors=Hogg; Tendal; Conway; Pomponi; van Soest; Krautter; and Roberts | year=2010 | title=Deep-sea sponge grounds: Reservoirs of Biodiversity | series=UNEP-WCMC Biodiversity| volume=32 | publisher=[[UNEP-WCMC]] | location=Cambridge, UK | isbn=978-92-807-3081-4}}</ref> but the habitat was first fully recognized, studied and described in detail around the [[Faroe Islands]] during the inter-Nordic BIOFAR 1 programme 1987–90.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Mass occurrences of large sized sponges (Porifera) in Faroe Island (NE-Atlantic) shelf and slope areas: characteristics, distribution and possible causes|last=Klitgaard|first=Anne|last2=Tendal|first2=Ole Secher|last3=Westerberg|first3=H.|publisher=University of Southampton|year=1997|isbn=|location=|pages=129–142}}</ref> These were called ''Ostur'' (meaning "cheese" and referring to the appearance of the sponges) by the local fishermen and this name has to some extent entered the scientific literature.<ref name=UNEP2010/> Sponge grounds were later found elsewhere in the Northeast Atlantic<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Klitgaard|first=A. B.|last2=Tendal|first2=O. S.|date=2004-04-01|title=Distribution and species composition of mass occurrences of large-sized sponges in the northeast Atlantic|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0079661104000680|journal=Progress in Oceanography|volume=61|issue=1|pages=57–98|doi=10.1016/j.pocean.2004.06.002}}</ref> and in the Northwest Atlantic,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Murillo|first=Francisco Javier|last2=Muñoz|first2=Pablo Durán|last3=Cristobo|first3=Javier|last4=Ríos|first4=Pilar|last5=González|first5=Concepción|last6=Kenchington|first6=Ellen|last7=Serrano|first7=Alberto|date=2012-11-01|title=Deep-sea sponge grounds of the Flemish Cap, Flemish Pass and the Grand Banks of Newfoundland (Northwest Atlantic Ocean): Distribution and species composition|url=https://dx.doi.org/10.1080/17451000.2012.682583|journal=Marine Biology Research|volume=8|issue=9|pages=842–854|doi=10.1080/17451000.2012.682583|issn=1745-1000}}</ref> as well as near Antarctica.<ref name=UNEP2010/> They are now known from many other places worldwide and recognized as key marine habitats.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://link.springer.com/referenceworkentry/10.1007/978-3-319-17001-5_24-1|title=Sponge Grounds as Key Marine Habitats: A Synthetic Review of Types, Structure, Functional Roles, and Conservation Concerns|last=Maldonado|first=Manuel|last2=Aguilar|first2=Ricardo|last3=Bannister|first3=Raymond J.|last4=Bell|first4=James J.|last5=Conway|first5=Kim W.|last6=Dayton|first6=Paul K.|last7=Díaz|first7=Cristina|last8=Gutt|first8=Julian|last9=Kelly|first9=Michelle|date=2015-01-01|publisher=Springer International Publishing|isbn=9783319170015|editor-last=Rossi|editor-first=Sergio|pages=1–39|language=en|doi=10.1007/978-3-319-17001-5_24-1|editor-last2=Bramanti|editor-first2=Lorenzo|editor-last3=Gori|editor-first3=Andrea|editor-last4=Valle|editor-first4=Covadonga Orejas Saco del}}</ref>
Sponge grounds are important habitats supporting diverse [[ecosystem]]s. During a study of [[outer shelf]] and upper [[Continental slope|slope]] sponge grounds at the Faroe Islands, 242 invertebrate species were found in the vicinity and 115 were associated with the sponges.<ref>{{cite journal| authors=Klitgaard, A.B. | year=1995 | title=The fauna associated with the outer shelf and upper slope sponges (Porifera, Demospongiae) at the Faroe Islands, Northeast Atlantic | journal=Sarsia| volume=80 | issue=1 | pages=1–22 | doi=10.1080/00364827.1995.10413574}}</ref> In general, fish fauna associated with sponge grounds are poorly known, but include [[Sebastes|rockfish]] and [[gadiform]]s.<ref name=UNEP2010/> Sponge grounds are threatened, especially by [[bottom trawling]] and other [[fishing tackle|fishing gear]], [[dredging]], [[oil and gas exploration]] and [[undersea cable]]s, but potentially also by [[deep sea mining]], [[carbon dioxide sequestration]], pollution and [[climate change]].<ref name=UNEP2010/>
== Prehisoric sponge grounds == By studying spicules in sediments cores taken from sponge grounds on the slopes of the [[Flemish Cap]] and [[Grand Banks of Newfoundland|Grand Bank]] (off Newfoundland, Canada), scientists managed to detect the presence of sponges in the past.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Murillo|first=F. J.|last2=Kenchington|first2=E.|last3=Lawson|first3=J. M.|last4=Li|first4=G.|last5=Piper|first5=D. J. W.|date=2016-02-29|title=Ancient deep-sea sponge grounds on the Flemish Cap and Grand Bank, northwest Atlantic|url=https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s00227-016-2839-5|journal=Marine Biology|language=en|volume=163|issue=3|pages=1–11|doi=10.1007/s00227-016-2839-5|issn=0025-3162|pmc=4771817|pmid=27065495}}</ref> The oldest record for [[Geodiidae]] sponges in this region was found in a long core collected in the slope of the Grand Bank, where typical [[sterraster]] spicules were found in the top of a submarine landslide deposit older than 25 000 BP. Continuous presence of sponges was recorded on the southeastern region of the Flemish Cap as far as 130 000 BP. It seems the distribution range of the [[Geodiidae]] in this area significantly expended after the deglaciation.
