'''Zoe Shipton''' is a British geologist. She is a professor of Geological Engineering at [[Strathclyde University]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Prof. Zoe Shipton |url=http://www.shaleuk.com/speaker/prof-zoe-shipton/ |title=Prof. Zoe Shipton &#124; Shale UK 2015 |publisher=Shaleuk.com |date= |accessdate=2014-08-10}}</ref> Shipton is a member of the [[Royal Society]] and [[Royal Academy of Engineering]] working group on “Shale gas extraction in the UK: a review of the scientific and engineering evidence” and currently holds the chair of the Tectonic Studies Group of the [[Geological Society of London]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shaleuk.com/speaker/prof-zoe-shipton/ |title=Prof. Zoe Shipton » Shale UK 2016 |website=Shaleuk.com |date= |accessdate=2016-03-16}}</ref>
In July 2014, Shipton's career in geology was featured on the [[BBC Radio 4]] show ''The Life Scientific''<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b048l0g3 |title=BBC Radio 4 - The Life Scientific, Zoe Shipton |website=Bbc.co.uk |date=2014-07-08 |accessdate=2016-03-16}}</ref>
==Honours== In March 2016 Shipton was elected a Fellow of the [[Royal Society of Edinburgh]], Scotland's National Academy for science and letters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.royalsoced.org.uk/1200_2016ElectedFellows.html |title=The Royal Society of Edinburgh &#124; 2016 Elected Fellows |website=Royalsoced.org.uk |date= |accessdate=2016-03-16}}</ref>
==Family== Zoe's paternal grandfather was Himalayan mountaineer, [[Eric Shipton]].<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b048l0g3 Shipton talks about her mountaineer grandfathers at 3'24"]</ref>
